# debounce_demo.a4 — Event debounce pipeline (inspired by BigVault)
#
# PURPOSE
# =======
# This demo implements a real-world event debouncing system: multiple rapid
# file-change notifications are batched into a single consolidated event
# emitted after a quiet period. This is the core pattern used in BigVault's
# storage monitoring subsystem for object storage change tracking.
#
# THE ORIGINAL PROBLEM (280 lines of Erlang)
# ==========================================
# In BigVault, an object storage monitor fires individual events each time a
# file is created, deleted, tagged, or processed. Under bulk upload this
# produces hundreds of events per second. A debounce actor accumulates them
# into a merged summary (net adds/deletes + size/count statistics) and emits
# one consolidated event after 1 second of quiet.
#
# The Erlang version requires:
#   - 25 lines of record definitions (4 nested records)
#   - 30 lines of gen_server boilerplate (init, handle_call, terminate, etc.)
#   - 15 lines of timer ref management (start, cancel, stale-ref guard)
#   - 150 lines of nested record update logic with intermediate variables
#   - No compile-time guarantee that all event types are handled
#   - No type safety at message boundaries between actors
#
# WHY ACTORFORTH IS DIFFERENT
# ===========================
# 1. Product types replace records — field access/update is native, no
#    intermediate variables needed for nested updates.
#
# 2. Actors are primitive — no gen_server boilerplate. The actor IS the
#    type instance; its state lives on the stack.
#
# 3. receive_match_timeout replaces manual timer management — block for
#    tagged messages up to N ms, then fall through. The entire timer
#    state machine (nil | reference, cancel, stale-ref guard) vanishes.
#
# 4. Typed messages — each event kind is a tagged Message. The debounce
#    actor dispatches by tag. Wrong message shapes are type errors, not
#    silent drops via a catch-all clause.
#
# 5. Strong types at actor boundaries — the Logger actor's interface is
#    defined by word signatures. You cannot send it a malformed event.
#
# ARCHITECTURE (4 actors)
# =======================
#
#   Simulator ──(tagged msgs)──> Debouncer ──(typed call)──> Logger
#                                    |                         |
#                                    └── receive_match_timeout │
#                                        (1s quiet period)     │
#                                                              v
#                                                          EventStore
#                                                        (receives logged
#                                                         summary events)
#
#   Simulator:  Fires rapid file events to the Debouncer's mailbox
#   Debouncer:  Accumulates events; emits summary after 1s of quiet
#   Logger:     Receives typed summary, forwards to EventStore
#   EventStore: Terminal sink — stores events (prints for demo)
#
# The entire pipeline is ~80 lines of ActorForth vs 280+ lines of Erlang.


# ============================================================
# Product Types — replace 4 Erlang records (25 lines of .hrl)
# ============================================================

# Per-file metadata accumulated during a debounce window
type Entry
    path String
    hash String
    size Int
    kind String .

# Running statistics for the debounce window
type Stats
    size_diff Int
    count_diff Int .

# Summary emitted after the quiet period
type Batch
    added Int
    deleted Int
    size_delta Int
    count_delta Int .

# Logger state — counts how many batches have been logged
type Tally
    batches Int .

# EventStore state — counts how many events have been stored
type Store
    events Int .


# ============================================================
# EventStore actor — terminal sink for logged events
# ============================================================

: record Store Int -> Store ;
    swap events rot + events! .

: total Store -> Store Int ;
    dup events .

0 store server
# EventStore actor is now on the stack


# ============================================================
# Logger actor — receives batch summaries
# ============================================================
# In production this would write to disk + publish to event bus.
# Here it just counts batches received to verify the pipeline.

: log_batch Tally Batch -> Tally ;
    drop batches 1 + batches! .

: logged Tally -> Tally Int ;
    dup batches .

0 tally server
# Logger actor is now on the stack (EventStore is below it)


# ============================================================
# Test: Product types
# ============================================================

# --- Batch construction and field access ---
# Getters are non-destructive: (Instance -- Value Instance)
5 3 200 2 batch
added 5 assert-eq
deleted 3 assert-eq
size_delta 200 assert-eq
count_delta 2 assert-eq
drop    # clean up Batch instance

# --- Stats ---
1024 1 stats
size_diff 1024 assert-eq
count_diff 1 assert-eq
drop    # clean up Stats instance

# --- Entry ---
"/docs/report.pdf" "abc123" 4096 "application/pdf" entry
path "/docs/report.pdf" assert-eq
hash "abc123" assert-eq
size 4096 assert-eq
kind "application/pdf" assert-eq
drop    # clean up Entry instance


# ============================================================
# Test: Logger actor (typed actor protocol)
# ============================================================
# The Logger only accepts (Tally Batch -> Tally). Sending it
# anything else is a type error — not a runtime crash from a
# catch-all clause, but a dispatch failure before the message
# is ever sent. This is the key difference from Erlang.

# Build a batch inside << >> and send it to the Logger
<< 5 3 200 2 batch log_batch >>

# Send a second batch
<< 10 1 500 9 batch log_batch >>

# Verify Logger received both batches
<< logged >> 2 assert-eq


# ============================================================
# Test: EventStore actor
# ============================================================

swap    # bring EventStore to top
<< 5 record >>
<< 3 record >>
<< total >> 8 assert-eq


# ============================================================
# Cleanup
# ============================================================

<< stop >> drop    # stop EventStore
<< stop >> drop    # stop Logger
